## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. Your `Stop()` method will silently fail to stop a blocked thread, and cleanup logic in the `catch` block will never execute.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop explicitly — no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait for graceful shutdown with a timeout
            if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
            {
                // Log warning: worker did not stop within timeout
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.GetAwaiter().GetResult(); // sync wait on dispose
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Issue | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` throws at runtime** | `PlatformNotSupportedException` — not a compile error, so it silently breaks in production |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a synchronous wait (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take()`), cancellation never interrupts it. Use the `CancellationToken` overload (`Take(token)`) or switch to `async` APIs (`ChannelReader.ReadAsync(token)`) |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent** | Not needed — `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception, not auto-rethrown |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | It can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` both signals and interrupts `async` waits |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Always store and await the `Task` — unobserved exceptions vanish silently |

### If You Must Keep Synchronous Code

For sync-only blocking calls that don't accept a `CancellationToken`, use a cooperative interrupt pattern:

```csharp
private Thread? _workerThread;

public void Stop()
{
    _cts.Cancel();
    if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
    {
        // Thread.Interrupt() unblocks Thread.Sleep / Monitor.Wait / WaitHandle
        // but NOT unmanaged or CPU-bound blocking
        _workerThread.Interrupt();
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Log: thread did not exit — cannot force-kill in .NET 8
        }
    }
}
```

> **Bottom line:** Replace `Thread` + `Abort()` with `Task` + `CancellationToken`. Thread every blocking call with the token so cancellation is cooperative and deterministic. There is no forced-termination equivalent in .NET 8 — design for graceful shutdown.
